 The book concludes with a coda on Alfred Lord Tennyson, which illustrates how the Victorian reception of Scott and Byron affected the most popular poetic genius of midcentury. Ultimately, The Perversity of Poetry uncovers how the shift to a rhetoric of health allowed critics to oppose what they perceived as a potent and potentially dangerous influence on the age, the very thing that would over the course of the century be marginalized into such obscurity: poetry, thanks to its perverse insistence on making something happen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.). 0aEnglish poetryxMale authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish poetryy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGenius in literature. 0aMasculinity in literature. 0aMen in literature. 0aPopular literaturezGreat BritainxHistory and criticism. 0aRomanticismzGreat Britain. 4aGeneral Interest : Poetry. 4aLiterature : English Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Romanticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791483978423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791483978/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles